Introduction data handling and graphical representation

Katharina Imkeller

15. June 2020

Data wrangling with dplyr

dplyr is an R package that allows easy manipulation of data tables. A set of commonly used dplyr commands can be found on the following summary: dplyr cheatsheet.

The dplyr functions are:

  • filter() picks cases based on their values.
  • summarise() reduces multiple values down to a single summary.
  • arrange() changes the ordering of the rows.
  • mutate() adds new variables that are functions of existing variables
  • select() picks variables based on their names.

The following script illustrate how to use these functions on a dataset containing information on different types of iris plants. This dataset is just for illustration purposes, because it is especially well suited to understand how dplyr is working. A similar introduction using a dataset about Starwars characters can also be found here: https://dplyr.tidyverse.org/.

Later on in the tutorial you will perform the same type of manipulations on a dataset of antibody reactivity data.

library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union

Filtering data tables

filter() picks cases (rows) based on their values. In all following example, the DT::datatable() function is there to display the tables in a readable way.

DT::datatable(
filter(iris, Species == "versicolor")
)

Usage of the %>% pipe:

DT::datatable(
iris %>%
    filter(Species == "versicolor")
)

Filters can be combined:

DT::datatable(
iris %>%
    # AND
    filter(Species == "versicolor" & Petal.Width < 1.2) 
)
DT::datatable(
iris %>%
    #  OR
    filter(Species == "versicolor" | Petal.Width < 1.2) 
)

Summarizing and grouping

summarise() reduces multiple values down to a single summary

DT::datatable(
iris %>%
  summarise(
    n = n(),
    meanSW = mean(Sepal.Width, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) 
)
DT::datatable(
iris %>%
  group_by(Species) %>%
    summarise(
    n = n(),
    meanSW = mean(Sepal.Width, na.rm = TRUE)
  )
)
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

arrange() changes the ordering of the rows

DT::datatable(
iris %>%
  group_by(Species) %>%
    summarise(
    n = n(),
    meanSW = mean(Sepal.Width, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
    arrange(meanSW)
)
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

Selecting columns

select() picks variables based on their names.

DT::datatable(
iris %>%
  select(Sepal.Width, Species)
)
DT::datatable(
iris %>%
  select(Species, ends_with("Width"))
)

Adding columns (mutating the table)

mutate() adds new variables that are functions of existing variables

DT::datatable(
iris %>%
  mutate(Sepal.Ratio = Sepal.Width/Sepal.Length) 
)

Generating graphics using ggplot2

ggplot2 is an R package for generating graphical representations of your data. A set of commonly used dplyr commands can be found on the following summary: ggplot2 cheatsheet.

library(ggplot2)

A ggplot2 command consists of following elements:

  • a ggplot() function that has the dataset (here iris) as first argument
  • an aesthetic mapping aes(), where you define the columns of the dataset that should be used as x, y, color, size
  • a layer, where you define what type of plotting functions should be used (layers can be overlayed)

The following code plots the sepal length as a function of sepal length. Every dot corresponds to one row of the dataset iris.

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
    geom_point()

The dots can be colored according to iris species:

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width, color=Species)) +
    geom_point()

A faceting specification (e.g.facet_wrap()) can be used to split the data into several plots:

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width, color=Species)) +
    geom_point() +
    facet_wrap(~Species)

The data can also be summarized into box-plots, by using the Species on the x axis:

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Species, y = Sepal.Length)) +
    geom_boxplot()

Overlaying dot-plots on top of the box-plot:

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Species, y = Sepal.Length)) +
    geom_boxplot() +
    geom_jitter()
